      <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       OVERVIEW — WHY RAJA AMPAT IS DIFFERENT
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section id="overview" class="section overview-section">
        <div class="section__inner">
          <div class="overview">
            <div class="overview__text">
              <span class="overview__label">The Coral Triangle</span>
              <h2>The World's Most Biodiverse Marine Ecosystem</h2>

              <p class="overview__lead">
                Raja Ampat isn't just another dive destination. It is, by every
                scientific measure, the richest marine environment on Earth—a
                place where the numbers defy belief and the reality exceeds
                expectation.
              </p>

              <p>
                Located at the heart of the Coral Triangle—the Amazon of the
                seas—Raja Ampat comprises over 1,500 islands scattered across
                40,000 square kilometers of West Papua's Bird's Head Peninsula.
                These waters contain <strong
                  >75% of all known coral species</strong
                > (over 600), more than <strong>1,600 fish species</strong>, and
                the kind of marine life density that has marine biologists
                genuinely struggling for superlatives.
              </p>

              <p>
                At Cape Kri, scientists recorded 374 fish species on a single
                dive—a world record that still stands. That's more species in 75
                minutes than exist in the entire Caribbean Sea.
              </p>

              <div class="overview__stats">
                <div class="overview__stat">
                  <div class="overview__stat-value">75%</div>
                  <div class="overview__stat-label">Global Coral Species</div>
                </div>
                <div class="overview__stat">
                  <div class="overview__stat-value">1,600+</div>
                  <div class="overview__stat-label">Fish Species</div>
                </div>
                <div class="overview__stat">
                  <div class="overview__stat-value">374</div>
                  <div class="overview__stat-label">Species, One Dive</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="overview__visual">
              <div class="overview__image-frame">
                <Image
                  src={wayagAerial}
                  alt="Aerial view of Wayag Islands' iconic karst limestone formations in Raja Ampat"
                />
              </div>
              <span class="overview__image-accent" aria-hidden="true"></span>
              <p class="overview__image-caption">
                The iconic karst formations of Wayag—Indonesia's most
                photographed seascape
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- FEATURED QUOTE — Full Width -->
      <section class="featured-quote">
        <div class="featured-quote__inner">
          <p class="featured-quote__text">
            "Raja Ampat is like diving in an aquarium, except every aquarium
            you've ever seen was just a pale imitation of what exists here
            naturally."
          </p>
          <span class="featured-quote__attribution"
            >— Dr. Gerald Allen, ichthyologist and co-discoverer of Raja Ampat's
            biodiversity</span
          >
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- WHY RAJA AMPAT IS DIFFERENT + PHOTO -->
      <section class="section section--white">
        <div class="section__inner">
          <div class="two-col-with-image">
            <div class="two-col-with-image__text">
              <h3>Why Raja Ampat Is Different</h3>

              <p>
                <strong>Convergence Zone:</strong> Raja Ampat sits where the Pacific
                and Indian Oceans meet, creating nutrient-rich upwellings that support
                extraordinary productivity. The currents that flow through channels
                like the Dampier Strait bring constant supplies of plankton, attracting
                filter-feeding mantas and fueling the entire food chain.
              </p>

              <p>
                <strong>Isolation:</strong> The region's remoteness has protected
                it from the overfishing and development that degraded reefs elsewhere.
                Traditional Papuan communities have practiced sustainable fishing
                for generations, and modern marine protected areas now formalize that
                protection.
              </p>

              <p>
                <strong>Habitat Diversity:</strong> Within a single anchorage, you
                might find coral walls, mangrove forests, seagrass beds, and sandy
                slopes—each supporting distinct communities. This habitat variety
                translates directly into species diversity.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="two-col-with-image__image">
              <Image
                src={coralReef}
                alt="Vibrant coral reef in Raja Ampat"
              />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- BEYOND THE UNDERWATER WORLD — Full Width Feature -->
      <section class="beyond-section">
        <div class="beyond-section__inner">
          <div class="beyond-section__content">
            <span class="beyond-section__label">Above the Surface</span>
            <h2>Beyond the Underwater World</h2>
            <p>
              While the diving draws most visitors, Raja Ampat's terrestrial
              beauty is equally extraordinary. The iconic karst limestone
              formations of Wayag—mushroom-shaped islands covered in dense
              vegetation, rising from impossibly turquoise lagoons—have become
              Indonesia's most photographed seascape.
            </p>
            <p>
              The region is also home to <strong
                >Wilson's Bird-of-Paradise</strong
              > and the <strong>Red Bird-of-Paradise</strong>—endemic species
              found nowhere else on Earth. Local guides can arrange predawn
              hikes to witness their remarkable courtship displays.
            </p>
            <div class="beyond-section__highlights">
              <div class="beyond-section__highlight">
                <div class="beyond-section__highlight-title">
                  Wayag Viewpoint
                </div>
                <div class="beyond-section__highlight-text">
